Here's a simple C++ program that uses recursion to calculate the nth Fibonacci number.

```cpp
// FibonacciSeries.cpp

#include <iostream>

// Function to calculate the nth Fibonacci number using recursion
int fibonacci(int n) {
    // Base cases: Fibonacci of 0 and 1 is 0 and 1 respectively
    if (n == 0) return 0;
    else if (n == 1) return 1;
    // Recursive case: Fibonacci of n is the sum of Fibonacci of n-1 and n-2
    else return fibonacci(n - 1) + fibonacci(n - 2);
}

int main() {
    int n;
    std::cout << "Enter the value of n: ";
    std::cin >> n;

    try {
        // Check for negative n and n > 92
        if (n < 0) throw 1;
        else if (n > 92) throw 2;

        int fib_number = fibonacci(n);
        std::cout << "Fibonacci number at position " << n << " is: " << fib_number << std::endl;

    } catch (int error) {
        if (error == 1) std::cout << "Error: n must be a non-negative integer." << std::endl;
        else if (error == 2) std::cout << "Error: n cannot be greater than 92 due to recursion limit." << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

This program calculates the nth Fibonacci number by breaking it down into smaller Fibonacci numbers until it reaches the base cases of n=0 or n=1. However, note that this recursive approach has a high time complexity of O(2^n) due to the repeated computation of the same Fibonacci numbers. It's not recommended for large values of n because it can cause a stack overflow.

If you need to compute large Fibonacci numbers efficiently, consider using iteration or memoization techniques.

